<td class="" style=""><a href="http://www.compiz.org" class="external text" title="http://www.compiz.org" rel="nofollow">compiz.org</a></td>
</tr>
</table>
<p><b>Compiz</b> is one of the first <a href="/wiki/Compositing_window_manager" title="Compositing window manager">compositing window managers</a> for the <a href="/wiki/X_Window_System" title="X Window System">X Window System</a> that uses <a href="/wiki/3D_graphics" title="3D graphics" class="mw-redirect">3D graphics</a> hardware to create fast <a href="/wiki/Compositing" title="Compositing">compositing</a> desktop effects for window management. The effects, such as a minimization effect and a cube workspace are implemented as loadable plugins. Because it conforms to the <a href="/wiki/Inter-Client_Communication_Conventions_Manual" title="Inter-Client Communication Conventions Manual">Inter-Client Communication Conventions Manual</a> standard, Compiz can substitute for the default <a href="/wiki/Metacity" title="Metacity">Metacity</a> in <a href="/wiki/GNOME" title="GNOME">GNOME</a> or <a href="/wiki/KWin" title="KWin">KWin</a> in <a href="/wiki/KDE" title="KDE">KDE</a>.</p>
<p>Some of its features mimic those of competitors, such as <a href="/wiki/Expos%C3%A9_(Mac_OS_X)" title="Exposé (Mac OS X)">Exposé</a> in <a href="/wiki/Apple_Computer" title="Apple Computer" class="mw-redirect">Apple</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Mac_OS_X" title="Mac OS X">Mac OS X</a> and an <a href="/wiki/Alt-Tab" title="Alt-Tab">Alt-Tab</a> application-switcher that uses live previews, instead of just icons. The Composite extension to X is used, as is the <a href="/wiki/OpenGL" title="OpenGL">OpenGL</a> extension <tt>GLX_EXT_texture_from_pixmap</tt> <sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup>. The first version of Compiz was released as <a href="/wiki/Free_software" title="Free software">free software</a> by <a href="/wiki/Novell" title="Novell">Novell</a> (<a href="/wiki/SUSE" title="SUSE" class="mw-redirect">SUSE</a>) in January 2006 in the wake of the also new <a href="/wiki/Xgl" title="Xgl">Xgl</a>.</p>
